It is officially logged. I have 2.3 flight hours ^_^
if I had to describe what it's like to fly a small aircraft, I would say it's like a mix of a motorcycle/quadracross and a boat 4,000 feet in the air.
On the ground, you're very fast immediately. Everything is a bit unstable on the ground, hence motorcycle/quadracross.
And if you didn't know: You steer an airplane on the ground with your feet, not with the yoke. Pedals and brakes. It's not a car.
In the air, it's wobbly and you're floating a bit. It feels like you're in a boat on water. You can control it, but sometimes a wave throws you off a little, so you basically have to get used to the sea motion, just in the air.
One more random detail:
Flying is physically demanding. My back and legs hurt today *weh*, as if I had been at the fitness studio.
This is not like a Sunday drive in the car. It's more of a sport than a leisurely ride, in my newly formed opinion.
A nice Saturday, my loves. Welcome at 4,000 feet.
Morning I will go again. Then we will practice stall and slow flight.
Today the weather was turbulent but it was lots of fun. We practiced slow flight and stall. Once we had a ground speed of only 16 mph at an airspeed of 65.
It was a beautiful clear day, a bit foggy higher up, but still beautiful.
